ntal prose invokes such diverse themes as: Greek mythology, the apocalypse, family dynamics, psychology, Russian history, theosophy, revolution, and European literary influences. Considered by Vladimir Nabokov to be one of the twentieth century’s four greatest masterpieces, Petersburg is the first novel in which the city is the hero. Frequently compared to Joyce’s Ulysses, no novel did more to help launch modernism in turn-of-the century Russia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aRussian prose literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh1 aAnschuetz, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeyer, Thomas R.1 aBeyer, Thomas R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarlson, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastellano, Charlene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooke, Olga M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooke, Olga M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEmery, Jacob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeys, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLangen, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLavrov, Aleksandr V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLjunggren, Magnus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNabokov, Vladimir, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPonomareva, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSteinberg, Ada, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeiner, Adam, econtributo